subsection.p:
We also explored how to scale a nonzero vector to a unit vector in . For example, if a vector has norm 1/2, then we can scale it up to a unit vector by multiplying it by 2 to double its norm. Conversely, if a vector has norm 2, we can scale it down to a unit vector by multiplying it by 1/2 to halve its norm. In general, we can scale any nonzero vector \uvec{v} in \R^n up or down to a unit vector by multiplying it by scale factor k=\frac{1}{\unorm{v}}, since then

	\norm{\frac{1}{\unorm{v}}\,\uvec{v}}
	= \abs{\frac{1}{\unorm{v}}}\,\unorm{v}
	= \frac{1}{\unorm{v}}\,\unorm{v}
	= 1.

In the above, we have used the formula for the norm of a scalar multiple, \norm{k\uvec{v}} = \abs{k}\unorm{v}, with k=\frac{1}{\unorm{v}}. The absolute value brackets on k could be removed because norms are never negative, and so \abs{k} = k in this case.

In fact, every nonzero vector \uvec{v} is parallel to exactly two corresponding unit vectors, because k\uvec{v} and -k\uvec{v} always have the same norm. So
\uvec{u}_1 \amp= \frac{1}{\unorm{v}}\,\uvec{v}, \amp \amp\text{and} \amp \uvec{u}_2 \amp= -\frac{1}{\unorm{v}}\,\uvec{v}
are always unit vectors, as long as \uvec{v} \neq \zerovec.

First, for a pair of nonzero vectors in \R^n, the formula
 \frac{\udotprod{u}{v}}{\unorm{u}\unorm{v}} 
can always be computed, and the result of the computation is always one, definite number.

Second, looking at the provided graph of y=\cos\theta, there are no instances in the domain 0\le\theta\le\pi where \cos\theta computes to the same value for two different values of \theta. On this domain, we call the graph one-to-one. So a pair of vectors in \R^n can never have two angles in the domain 0\le\theta\le\pi between them, because there are never two solutions to the equation

	\cos\theta = \frac{\udotprod{u}{v}}{\unorm{u}\unorm{v}}

in that domain.

But is there always some solution to that equation? No matter what domain you work on, \cos\theta never evaluates to a number greater than 1 or less than -1. Perhaps if we tried hard enough we could discover some unlucky pair of vectors \uvec{u} and \uvec{v} in \R^13 where
 \frac{\udotprod{u}{v}}{\unorm{u}\unorm{v}} 
computed to a number greater than 1 or to a number less than -1. In that case, it would be impossible for \cos\theta to be equal to that number, and \uvec{u} and \uvec{v} would have no angle between them. It turns out that finding such an unlucky pair of vectors is impossible, and we know this courtesy of a couple of dead guys.

statement.p:
For every pair of vectors \uvec{u} and \uvec{v} in \R^n, the quantity
 \frac{\udotprod{u}{v}}{\unorm{u}\unorm{v}} 
is always between -1 and 1 (inclusive).

ul.li:
It might seem more natural to use

	\udotprod{u}{v} \,=\, \utrans{\uvec{u}}\uvec{v}
	\,=\,
	\begin{bmatrix}u_1 \amp u_2 \amp \cdots \amp u_n\end{bmatrix}
	\begin{bmatrix}v_1\\v_2\\\vdots\\v_n\end{bmatrix}
	\,=\, u_1 v_1 + u_2 v_2 + \dotsb u_n v_n

(as we did in ),
instead of the seemingly pointless reversal of order in the formula
\udotprod{u}{v} = \utrans{\uvec{v}}\uvec{u}.
However, if you continue on in your study of linear algebra beyond this course, you will discover that this reversal of order is absolutely necessary when studying complex vectors (that is, vectors where the components are complex numbers). Since this reversal of order is harmless here, we will start using it now so as to avoid confusion later.
